'The sea is ours': Bolivia hopes court will open waterway to Pacific
Sailors patrol naval headquarters in La Paz.
Public buildings flags with ocean blue flags.
Marine bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon River are covered with the motto: "The sea is ours. We are right
and duty to return to it."
In landlocked Bolivia, the people can still recall a coastline lost to Chile, in a bloody 19th-century conflict over resources, longing to sail the Pacific once again.
These hopes are perhaps stronger than in many decades while Bolivia awaits the verdict of the International Court of Justice due on October 1, after five years of deliberation.
"Bolivia has drive, serenity and is united, and of course expects a positive result," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
