The Netherlands-based UN court does not have the power to transfer Chilean territory to Bolivia, and has stipulated that they will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The fact that the court's ruling comes just six months after the latest negotiations indicates that the case "wasn't complicated," said Paz Z<0xC3><0xA1>rate, a Chilean expert in international law.
The last four years have far from advanced Bolivia's case, they have done the opposite.
"The problem of access to the sea has been taken over by the current Bolivian administration," said Z<0xC3><0xA1>rate.
Morales, with his belligerent rhetoric, has killed what was left of Chile's goodwill, Z<0xC3><0xA1>rate thought.
Bolivia and Chile will continue negotiations at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to discuss the issue after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
The former president, Eduardo Rodr<0xC3><0xAD>guez Veltzé, who is Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the Court's decision was unusually quick.
On Monday, Bolivia will have "an extraordinary opportunity to open new relations with Chile" and a chance to "set a bar at 139 years of impropriety and rather benefit both of them," he said.
Calzadilla also rejected that Morales, who remains one of the most popular presidents in Latin America, used this maritime issue to win votes.
