John Edward: Global citizens need language skills
Private schools in Scotland are known to be at a high academic level, and this continues in 2018 with excellent graduation results, which are only enhanced by individual and joint success in sport, art, music and other community measures.
With over 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), work to provide the best services to students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for advanced and higher education, career paths, and the role of global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailored curriculum, we see that modern languages are popular electives in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, the message goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, the message goes to his heart."
This is an important reminder that we can't just lean on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
By looking at the exam results from this year, we can see that language is at the top of the league tables with the highest passing grades for independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who took foreign languages received A.
The data, collected from SCIS' 74 member schools, show that 72 percent of students received A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who took German, 69 percent of those who took French, and 63 percent of those who took Spanish also received A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital assets, which children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Languages as electives are considered equivalent to the STEM (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics) subjects in the curriculum of independent schools and elsewhere.
A survey carried out by the British Committee for Employment and Properties in 2014 showed that 17 per cent of employers were struggling to fill positions due to a lack of language skills among applicants.
Therefore, it is more and more important with language in school to prepare the youth for the workplace.
With multiple job opportunities for language savvy, these properties are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what kind of career a youth chooses, if they have learned a second language, they have an orderly advantage in the future with such a property.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give a multilingual person advantages in a competitive world.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adult Britons in 2013, 75 percent could speak no language other than English well enough to keep a conversation going, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15 percent.
This is why it is so important to invest in language learning for our children.
Knowledge of several languages, especially the languages used in developing countries, can give children a better chance of finding good jobs in the future.
In Scotland, each school is different in terms of the languages they teach.
Many schools focus on the classic modern languages, while others teach languages that are classified as important in the UK as we look forward to 2020, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
No matter what your child is interested in, there will always be a plethora of languages to choose from in independent schools, and teachers who are specialists in this area.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated and want to create a learning environment that will prepare children and provide them with the properties they need to succeed, whatever the future brings.
It cannot be denied that in this global, business-oriented environment, languages are vital to the future of the country, so this must be reflected in the education sector.
Modern languages should be called "international communication properties."
Independent schools will continue to offer this option, thus offering diversity and high skills for Scotland's young.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
