North Korea says there will be no talk of arming down unilaterally without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told Saturday to the United Nations that if sanctions continue, distrust of the United States will grow and that it would by no means give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual general assembly of the world government that North Korea had taken "significant measures" to improve conditions over the past year, for example, they have stopped nuclear and missile tests, dismantled that nuclear test site and do not promise to disperse nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we are not getting anything equivalent back from the United States," he said.
"Without confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances, it is not possible that we unilaterally disarm first."
While Ri, a noted North Korean, has made several complaints about Washington's opposition to a "phased" approach to nuclear disarmament, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking gradual steps, his dissent proved significant in that he did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri was referring to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at a first-ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on 12 June, when Kim promised to work for "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's safety.
North Korea has wanted a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted talks to ease tough international sanctions in North Korea.
"The United States insists on "nuclear decommissioning first" and increases the pressure with sanctions to achieve its purpose by force, and they even opposed the "declaration to make peace," Ri said.
"The belief that sanctions can crack us is a false hope among those who are not interested in us.
But the problem is that when sanctions continue, our distrust only grows."
Ri did not mention anything about plans for another summit between Kim and Trump, which the US president highlighted at the UN earlier this week.
The minister instead emphasized three meetings between Kim and South Korea's leader, Moon Jae-in, over the past five months and added: "If the party in this call to nuclear disarmament was South Korea, and not the United States, the dismantling on the Korean peninsula would not have stopped as it has now done"
Yet the tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year, when he told the U.N. General Assembly that there was no way to stop North Korean missiles against the U.S. mainland, after evil-doing President Trump called Kim a rocket man on a suicide mission.
Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, lavished praise on Kim for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said that much work still had to be done and that sanctions had to remain in place until North Korea dismantles its nuclear weapon.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a timeframe for this, saying, "If it takes two years, three years, or five months, no matter."
China and Russia claim that the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures that have been taken.
However, United States Secretary of State, Mike Pompeo, told the U.N.'s Security Council on Thursday that: "The sanctions of the Security Council must still be maintained vigorously and without fail until we get the complete, final, verified decommissioning of the nuclear weapons."
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to throttle funds for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the U.N. General Assembly and said afterwards that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for another summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times already this year, but his last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July and said that progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea condemns him for making "gangster-like demands."
North Korea promised in a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States took "equivalent measures."
He said Kim had told him that the "equivalent measures" he was seeking were security guarantees promised by Trump in Singapore, and steps towards normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take classes in getting enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has helped all students get more sleep, in an attempt to fight the growing macho culture of studying in caffeine rushes all night, meaning that you use caffeine to stay awake all night to study.
One academic found that students at top universities are often careless when it comes to the very basics—how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a Brigham and Women's Hospital specialist, developed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact sleep deprivation has on learning.
"At the end of it, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why am I being told this now, in adulthood?'
She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, rolled out for the first time this year, explains to students what is important for how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the university's health services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after students got seriously worse sleep during the week.
The hour-long course involves a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a dormitory, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers, and books to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation, as well as the importance of evening routines.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
'We know it won't change the behaviour of students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know, the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes, Prof. Czeisler added.
The pride culture of the 24 hours still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students mean that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Ensuring you get enough, good quality sleep should be the student's secret weapon against stress, fatigue, and anxiety, he said—even avoiding gaining weight, since sleep deprivation puts the brain into a state of starvation and makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, after being a student with him last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to push for a course for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all doctoral students to complete a similar program of study before they start at the prestigious institution.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students should consider setting an alarm for when to go to bed, and also for when to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" coming from electronic screens and LED lighting, which can completely reset the internal clock, leading to problems falling asleep.
