Almanac: Inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page from our "Sunday Morning" Almanac: 30 September 1882, 136 years ago today, and WE ARE RECOVERING ... the day when the one who would become the physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method to detect and measure radioactivity, an invention that ultimately led to the apparatus known as the Geiger counter.
As a scientific pillar ever since then, the Geiger counter also became a pillar of pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", with the seemingly untruthfully pretended cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: "What on earth is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, it can be used to find radioactive minerals, for example uranium.
When you put these earphones on, you can actually hear the effects of the atoms caused by the radioactivity in the minerals."
Evans: "Yes, now it's bubbling!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name lives on.
New cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to "see" red cells.
New cancer vaccine may teach immune system to 'see' red cells and kill them
Vaccines teach the immune system to recognize red cells, as part of the treatment
The method involves extracting immune cells from a patient, and changing them in the laboratory
They can then see a protein that is common in many cancers, and then reinject
A trial vaccine shows promising results in patients with a variety of cancers.
A woman treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize red cells, experienced the ovarian cancer disappearing for more than 18 months.
The method involves extracting immune cells from a patient, changing them in the laboratory, allowing them to "see" a protein common in many cancers, called HER2, and then reinjecting the cells.
Professor Jay Berzofsky, of the US National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine."
HER2 "drives the growth of several types of cancer, including breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancers, Professor Berzofsky explained.
A similar approach to extracting immune cells from patients and "learning" them how to target cancer cells, has worked in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
