Update on dinoflagellates: Concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (FWC) shows a general reduction in the concentration of dinoflagellates in the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, uneven conditions for growth are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte, and the counties around Collier - suggesting a reduction in concentration.
A growth of dinoflagellates spreads out approximately 200 miles on the coastline from northern Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
Areas of dinoflagellates are found approximately 10 miles (16 km) off the coast at Hillsborough, but compared to the previous week, there are fewer areas.
Dinoflagellates have also been observed in Pasco.
There have been reports of medium concentration in the Pinellas in the past week, low to high concentration along the coast in Hillsborough, low concentration in Manatee, high concentration along the coast in Sarasota, medium concentration in Charlotte, high concentration in Lee, and low concentration in Collier.
Respiratory irritation is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Respiratory tract irritation was not reported in the northwest of Florida in the past week.
